title: DBot 3rd Lead Screw Belt Tensioner (easier print)

description.text:
Slight modification of original files to make it slightly easier to print. The parts have been reoriented to lay flat on the bed and a sacrificial bridge layer has been added to the tensioner nut holes so that the circular nut holes above them print nicely. Just trim out the bridge layer with a drill or xacto knife.

The size of your build area will determine the length of belt you need. I have 300mm cubed and a 1220mm looped belt Was just enough to provide the triangle arrangement shown. A longer belt will give you more options but may require a separate tensioner if the sliding plate isn't enough to take up the slack.

You may be able to get away with 400mm screws depending on the length of your hotend and the motor/rod mounts you use and the thickness of the bed surface. I chose 500mm because I am using a dual flanged bearing mount and a Titan aero. A single flanged bearing block and a standard v6 would let you use 400mm.

Update: I switched to a longer 1500mm belt and moved the position of the leadscrew and motor mounts forward. (see the pictures 1-3 compared to pictures 4-6)

Features

Top hole for access to Anet V1.0 Board USB Port and Micro SD slot.
Bottom holes for power cables to enter the case. Positioned to line up with the power input on the main board and power inputs on the Mosfets.
Holes in the interior. They are positioned to allow cables to be fed through from the inside of your printer enclosure to the relevant points on the main board.
Mounting posts for the above mentioned boards.
Positions to screw the lid onto the case.
4 M3 holes to mount the box to the side of your enclosure.

The Lid features a position for mounting an 80mm fan above the main board. and slots below to improve airflow.

You will also need:

M3 screws - around 10mm long for the case lid (4) and around 8mm long for mounting the boards (12).
Screws suitable for the fan you wish to mount.

Updates - 18/11/2017

  • Modified how corners are handled. There was a positional error which manifested as a 0.5mm offset in both horizontal axes for the corner detail. Corners are now positioned correctly and are changed to round the number of edges to a multiple of 4 so that the edges of the corner align with the box edges.
  • Modified positioning of screw holes for the lid. I believe this now ensures you can access all of the screw holes for securing your boards!
  • Mirrored relevant changes to the generic project box template.

title: Marrakech Board Game (Assam and Dice game Pieces)

description.text:
Description:
In Marrakech each player takes the role of a salesperson who tries to outwit the others. In turn, each player rolls the dice and then moves Assam, the market organizer. If Assam stops on an opponent’s rug, the player must make a payment to its owner before putting one of their own rugs on an adjacent space. When the last rug has been laid, the total number of visible rugs and the number owned by each salesperson are added up.
Set Up:
Setting up a game of Marrakech is super simple.
Each player begins 30 Dirhams (money) and a set of colored rugs. The number of rugs each player will use in a game depends on the number of players (15 rugs each in a 2- 3-player game and 12 rugs each in a 4-player game).
Players then place the market organizer, Assam, in the center of the board and they’re ready to play.
If Assam lands on another player’s rug, the active player must pay that player for landing on their rug. The cost is equal to the total number of connected rug squares of the color landed on.
For example, if Assam lands on a red rug and there are 4 other red rug squares showing that are connected to that space, the player would pay 5 Dirhams to the red rug’s owner.
The next step in a player’s turn is to place one of their rugs in the market.
The player lays one of their rugs next to the space Assam ended on. Each rug will cover two squares. An edge of the newly placed rug must be next to Assam’s square. The rug may be placed on empty squares or over other rugs. The only restriction when placing a rug is that it may not fully cover an opponent’s single rug.
Then it’s the next player’s turn.
Game End:
Once players have placed all their rugs, the game ends.
Each half of a rug (1 square) showing and each Dirham count as 1 point.
Players count up the number of their rug squares showing on the board and add that amount to their stash of money. The player with the highest amount wins!

Contents:
1 board, 60 cloth rugs (4 sets of 15), 20($1) pieces, 20($5) pieces,
1 Assam game piece and 1 dice (sides numbered 1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4 )

Game Inventor: Dominque Ehrhard

Awards:
2014 Juego del Año Finalist
2010 Hungarian Board Game Award Nominee
2009 Mensa Select Winner
2009 Japan Boardgame Prize U-more Award Nominee
2008 Spiel des Jahres Nominee
2008 Spiel der Spiele Game of the Year Winner
2008 As d'Or - Jeu de l'Année Winner
2008 As d'Or - Jeu de l'Année Nominee

This is a fun and fairly easy game to make. all you really need is a 7 x 7 square board and small pieces of colored fabric or paper to represent the carpets. The main game piece Assam and the die are specific to the game at the die only goes from 1 to 4. You can decorate or design your Assam game piece however you want. Included are also some simple tokens (Dirhams) for game play if you want to use them but any coin is usable.

title: Heatbrake manifold for the Creality Stock Hotend
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Creality stock print head, for all it's faults, performs reasonably well, but on of it's subtler problems is how the airflow is managed . . .

or better said, how it's not managed at all. The fan is roughly positioned sorta in front of the heatbrake and hotend (which is insulated or the hotend wouldn't hold temp at all), and has an out of the way exhaust vents that no air exhausts through. Instead, the air mostly spills downward . . . Right onto your parts and heatbed.

"Hey great!" you say, "it doesn't have a separate part fan, so it does double duty!". Not so fast. There are reasons most printers have a separate part fan -- the heatbrake fan ALWAYS needs to be on when the hotend is heated, but in many cases you'll want to turn your part fan on/off/half-way . . . like for first layers, fine tuned bridging and Materials that shrink and crack . . .

So what do we do?!? This part is a quick print on an inkjet/laser printer that you cut out, glue the pattern to a piece of aluminum from a Coke can (ok, any brand will do) then cut and fold. Finish off with a few pieces of aluminum tape to seal the trickier gaps and then all of the air blows up and away from the bed and printing part.

This might have been printable out of a high temp plastic and insulated, but the aluminum is cheap, available everywhere for nothing, and can take the heat without worry.

An overview video is here: https://youtu.be/njiKf5o3naM

Step 1: print, glue, and cut

Print the page out, and check the scale (black/white bar should be in centimeters), and rough cut the excess papaer away form the part. Spray with an adhesive (or use gluestick -- you know you've got plenty) and let it dry. Note the markings for mountain and valley folds. Cut the aluminum/paper piece along the cut lines (outer perimeter).

Do not remove the paper when it's cut out.

Rough cut and glued onto a Coke can trimmed to the cut lines, we're ready to fold! Step 2: Fold

*note you don't have to be super accurate on this, but try to make the crease lines straight and crisp. I folded mine with one side of the line flat on a metal ruler to get the crisp folds shown below.

Starting at the diagonal panel, fold one line at a time 90 degrees in the direction indicated -- the third fold line (a valley) will eventually fold 180, but start at 90, then after the next fold, complete the third fold. all the rest are 90's in the direction indicated.

First fold -- Mountain. Second fold -- Valley Third fold - valley *just 90 degrees for now, we'll come back to this fold and finish it after the next fold Forth fold -- Mountain Back to the third fold -- crease it flat. the baffle side is done. Fifth Fold -- Mountain. Sixth fold -- Valley And we're Done! ready to install! Step 3: install tape behind the heatbrake and wires

Add a strip of aluminum tape (~1cm x a bit longer than it needs to be) just above the hot-end (Mine was partially stuck onto the hotend and to the back mounting plate) and run a strip of AL tape between the cables and the heatbrake, back to the mounting plate to seal up that back corner.

Dry-fit the manifold (the folded aluminum piece) -- the tab should slip under the fan mount at the bottom, the flat plate should sit above the hot-end on the front and the diagonal wall should go from the front corner to one corner of the heatbrake, funneling the air.

Step 4: install and test -- tape to seal

slip the cowling with the manifold on, trying to get the tape on the back to line up and overlap with the manifold as it all comes together.

Power on, and check for gaps or airflow out of the bottom of the print head. seal any gaps with small patches of AL tape . ..

. . . and you should now have a calm print bed when the howling blowdryer is cooling the heatbrake. You should now have better success with ABS and hotter plastics, better first layer adhesion on all prints, and your heatbed should heat up MUCH faster when homed. If you print a separate part fan on the side, you should have better control of cooler plastics and edges and bridging.

I first noticed this problem on my third print with ABS -- first went OK, but there was a bit of warping and cracking, all toward one corner of the parts . . . then on the next print I tried to start the print in HOME . . . and the bed never came up to temp.

Odd. it's reached temp pretty quickly before, why not now? then I noticed lowering the bed, the heat rose fairly quickly . . . and that it's a bit windy underneath the printhead.

Not good.

Nescessity is the motehr of invention, and whil I ;like my 3d printer immensely, I don't treat it like a hammer in search of nail-shaped problems. if the problem looks like a screw, out comes the drill-driver instead.

I didn't like the idea of a plastic manifold resting right up against the hotend, and I've done a bit of Origami and light metalwork before . . . envisioned the shape, drew out the major panels in a rough sketch, then connected them together as they would fold up.

I then Took the rough sketch, made some measurments and fillde in blanks -- how big each piece would be -- then plugged that all into a CAD.

Print, fold and test for fit . . . fix then repeat until it was close . . . then cut open a Coke can and try it for real :)

description.text:
An attempt at building a mould to cast OpenForge streets out of plaster.

I am finding that to make the openforge shapes work on OpenScad, I must use Meshmixer 'make solid' to completely resample the shape to get a manifold. From there, Meshlab 'laplacian smooth' and 'quadric edge collapse decination' produces a workably simple mesh.

These meshes can be subtracted from the mould lower texture by editing the openSCAD, or can be subtracted form the 'no texture' STL and then flipped upside-down for printing.

The "no texture" STL is positioned such that if an OpenForge piece is placed with a corner at 0,0,0, it should subtract correctly. The OpenForge pieces are positioned at various places, but those places seem to be multiples of 25mm, so it's relatively easy to line them up. Or you cvan use a bit of software to align the piece at the origin: I think I wrote a java app to do it, which is laying about somewhere on my hard drive somewhere.

21-Nov-2017:
Ok. Separating the mould is a pain, so I have added tabs onto the side pieces to grab onto.
The hemispheres in the base were too high and interfered with the texture. I have removed them.
I have increased the sliding clearance to .5mm. I should rename the variable - this is a fitting clearance, not a sliding clearance.
I have decreased the texture relief. The 'gutter tee' texure was clipping with the old setting.
The 'make solid, laplace smooth, decimate points' procedure seems to work. I set the lapalce smooth to 1 pass only, and decimate down to .1 of the points created by the 'make solid' opreration.

23-Nov-2017
Having an open top and trowillng it smooth definitely works better. I am using cooking spray as mould release.
I think I'll mark this project as no longer a work in progress at this point. There are a couple of mould examples, but I'm not going to process all the OpenForge textures and turn them into moulds, so I'll just leave the two that I have done here.

description.text:
Update Jan 2018. After repeated attempts to get a belt driven ebike working and having at least 2 belts break, I have come to the conclusion that it's simply not worth it to go belt driven. Just get a hub motor and be done with all the headache and time wasted.

---------------OLD description below------------------

This is a parametric version of the pulley used in StatonFrames pulley. Now you can choose the number of spokes and locations of the zip ties and stuff for you specific bike.
The conversion is VERY finicky. I'd recommend printing out a profile test of the pulley before committing the plastic for a full pulley and check for fit. Be prepared to spent lots of time on this project.
I also redid the motor mount. I am actually not happy with it currently but I will post it and it might be okay for someone else. The plastic motor mount flexes too much and I switched to a metal motor mount with plastic clamps to mount to the frame tube. Will post pictures soon.
The motor mount was made in autodesk inventor. You'll need autodesk inventor if you want to change some parameters in that.
There's also a motor fan if you want to use that. It should improve motor cooling.

The hardware:

  • 4 x 2 1/4" 5/16 bolts OR M8 metric equivalent
  • 1 x 5/16 bolt for bearings (length depends on # of bearings used for idler)
  • 2-3 x 608 bearings
  • 5/16 washers and nuts

This is a remix of Doctorgear63's Nerdcube Nerd Cube which has slightly thicker corners to make sure they are sturdy and do not break off after printing.

Replicating the model was easy. First off, I used TinkerCAD just because it was quick and easy. No reason to bring out AutoCAD for this.

Anyways, I started by making a 50 X 50 X 50mm cube. Then, using TCAD's SVG import, I imported the logo then stretched it to be 43 X 43 X 2mm. Then I turned the logo into a hole for the next step. (I got the logo here: https://goo.gl/x7pko4). Next, I created another cube 43 X 43 X 2mm and aligned it to center around the logo then grouped them. Now take that group and turn it into a hole.

Now I took the logo, copied it 4 more times for a total of 5 sides then used the align feature to align them in such a way that 1mm is inside the model and 1mm outside (easy to grab and move and prevents some grouping problems).

Finally, group it all together and export as STL.

If you want to breed your seeds quickly and properly you might consider using that germination box. It consist out of 2 parts, the box itself which has 4 arms to place on a warm heating system. Cover the box with tinfoil and place the frame over to fix it.
You need to place a sheet of paper in it. On top of that place your seeds, and put water on the paper. The paper shouldn't swim. Once a day you need to open the box to check everything went well and replace the air inside. This avoids molding inside. You can also check with your nose if it smells weird, if so then its probably to much water in it. If you're unsure with this procedure search the web there a dozen of good tutorials about.
